  "verdict": "correct",
  "notes": "The final count is correct: the number of paths from \u200b(0,0)\u200b to \u200b(n,n)\u200b satisfying \u200b b\\ge a-1\u200b equals \n\$$\\binom{2n}{n}-\\binom{2n}{n+2}=\\frac{1}{n+2}\\binom{2n+2}{n+1}=C_{n+1}.\$$\nThe reflection/bijection idea is valid: a bad path first hits the line \u200b b-a=-2\u200b at some \u200b(k,k-2)\u200b; swapping R/U in the suffix changes the endpoint from \u200b(n,n)\u200b to \u200b(n+2,n-2)\u200b, giving \u200b\\binom{2n}{n+2}\u200b bad paths. The algebraic simplification to the Catalan form is also correct, and small-\u200bn checks match.",
  "suggestions": "Clarify the bijection/inverse more explicitly: given a path to \u200b(n+2,n-2)\u200b, take its *first* visit to \u200b b-a=-2\u200b and swap the remaining steps back to recover a unique bad path. Also briefly note the degenerate case \u200bn=1\u200b where \u200b(n+2,n-2)\u200b has negative y, though the binomial coefficient convention yields 0 bad paths as desired."
}

